            "answer_text": "Yes. Besides the fact that \u201ccryptography\u201d is a really big field, even if we focus on public-key cryptography (which is likely what you had meant), there exist protocols which are not known to be breakable efficiently even assuming an efficient factorization algorithm. Some of the most well-known such protocols go by the name Elliptic-curve cryptography, and they rely on the hardness of inverting the \u201cmultiply-by-[math]m[/math]\u201d operation on the group of points of an elliptic curve over a finite field. (This is sometimes called the \u201cdiscrete logarithm problem over elliptic curves\u201d but that\u2019s a pretty confusing name.) And there are various other methods, such as NTRU. Mapping out the possibilities for public-key protocols and the (presumably) hard problems they rely on is an active field of research. ",
